AGI-&nbsp;&nbsp; "From local movement, now, we are a national political formation. And this is our strength. A force necessary to face international and European battles." It is what Matteo Salvini claims, interviewed by Aurora Lussana, in the book 'L'Umberto. The man who invented the North, out on April 16 for Piemme.
&nbsp;
"There is a continuity that is our goal: to approach power to citizens. This is the essence of everything - says the Leghista secretary -. And you can call it as you want, federalism, secession, devolution, macroregion because the League over the years has changed many political tactics but the goal, I would say eternal, remains to give voice to the territories". "We're the oldest party in Parliament and we'll still be for a long time," he adds.
&nbsp;
"The reaction of strong powers, judiciary, high finance, witnesses how much we are still perceived as alternatives to a certain system. Despite the League being to the government of the country, the Regions and the first five hundred mayors, I feel hostility by some kind of elite," says Salvini. "I think of the media system In short, being a popular force, of powerful friends we do not have but perhaps it is the fate of militants, and therefore also mine, expects us a demanding but extraordinary life". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2> A book celebrates Umberto Bossi</h2>
A novel of the origins but also a chronicle of the present with interviews to all the big of the League, looking for a vision for the future. It's the book 'L'Umberto. The man who invented the North, written by Aurora Lussana, published by Piemme, in the library since April 16. Militante since 1994, former director of 'Telepadania', first, and the 'Padania', then, Lussana aims to 'explain the first forty years of the League, which are celebrated today, through stories and anecdotes, also unpublished, aimed at tracing the style and character of its founder, Umberto Bossi. From the book emerges the image of a "man" whose life is indissolubly linked to his "political creation", the League. A leader who spent the night reviewing the intervention for Pontida's gathering and at two o'clock in the morning called the secretary.
&nbsp;
"Are you sleeping? But I must write Pontida's speech - he protested -. And then let me bring a sandwich I have to have dinner. Yeah, dinner. They're eating in America if you want me to put the clock on Milwaukee's casting." And then Bossi's love for the language and the Lombard people, the obsession for the structure and organization of the party, the control of the campaigns and posters, but also the invention of the Padana iconography, the relationship with farmers, and with the press (these "arms" of journalists, with whom he had, in reality, one of the closest relationships ever had by a political leader in Italy). The book appears as a path of self-analysis of a community but also personal for Lussana, who has worked for years in the secretariat of Bossi, before heading for the Padan media.
&nbsp;
"I told the love story between Umberto Bossi and his creature. His League, to which he ripped everything. A leghist novel, a tribute to man more than politicians," writes the author. 'L'Umberto' concludes with unpublished interviews to all big leghisti: Matteo Salvini, Roberto Calderoli, Giancarlo Giorgetti, Lorenzo Fontana, the governors Luca Zaia, Attilio Fontana and Massimiliano Fedriga, and the group leaders of Chamber and Senate, Riccardo Molinari and Massimiliano Fedriga. The book is "an authentic and rich portrait of anecdotes in which the whole world of Bossiano is reconstructed and the pre-political background noise of the League that today finds itself, forty years after its foundation on April 12, 1984, to hold the oldest symbol present in Parliament - is read in the back cover -. The homage to the founder of a journalist who followed him from the beginning, as a young militant, to tell of a movement in which perhaps nothing remains of the origins. Or perhaps in which everything remained unchanged in the seal of eternal legism."
<br> "I think in Milan that has always tended to live without Rome - observes Giorgetti -. In the end, Bossi had given a partisan structure to this opposition and by now that message has become a patrimony of all because &nbsp; there is no longer the fence of the League movement to contain it and perhaps now, in many can not say legist. Even those who don't vote for us, maybe he's a bit of a legist. Because&nbsp; leghismo is a background noise that always remains, a forest call, forest as a place of roots to return to".
<br> "Always remember that I trust more of the people with the vestor than the one with a nice dress", said the senatur to the secretary.&nbsp;

